            "title": "U.S. Wholesale Inventories Flat in August",
            "description": "<div class=\"txt-s4 article-text\"><p>\n  By Don Nico Forbes </p><br/><p>\n  U.S. wholesale inventories were flat in August, according to delayed data published Friday by the Commerce Department. </p><!-- Article --><p>\n\n  The reading follows a 0.1% rise in July. Economists polled by The Wall Street Journal had expected a fall of 0.2%. </p><p>\n\n  The gauge is a metric in calculating the U.S.'s quarterly gross domestic product, which reflects the health of the economy. </p><p>\n\n  Inventories of durable goods--products made to last longer than three years--rose by 0.1%, compared with a 0.2% fall in July. Durable goods are often seen as more exposed to tariffs on foreign imports. </p><p>\n\n  Nondurable inventories fell by 0.1%, compared with a downwardly revised 0.6% jump in July. Drug inventories fell 1.8%. </p><p>\n\n  The ratio of inventories to sales--measuring how many months it would take for wholesalers to sell current stocks--was 1.28, unchanged from July. </p><p>\n\n  The release of wholesale inventories was originally scheduled for Oct. 9, but was delayed due to the government shutdown. </p><br/><p>\n  Write to Don Nico Forbes at don.forbes@wsj.com </p><br/><p>\n  (END) Dow Jones Newswires</p><p>\n\n  11-21-25 1033ET</p></div>",
            "link": "https://hk.marketscreener.com/news/u-s-wholesale-inventories-flat-in-august-ce7d5edfdc8bfe21",
